Task 1: Access the Linux System Physically
Subtask 1.1: Power On the System
Ensure the Linux system is powered on.
If using a virtual machine (e.g., VirtualBox, KVM), start the VM.
Subtask 1.2: Reach the Login Prompt
After booting, the system will display a login prompt (text-based or graphical).
If using a graphical login screen, press Ctrl + Alt + F2 to switch to a text-based terminal (tty2).
Expected Outcome:

You should see a login prompt similar to:
Fedora 38 (Workstation Edition)  
Kernel 6.2.15-200.fc38.x86_64 on an x86_64 (tty2)  

localhost login: _  
Troubleshooting Tip:

If the system boots to a graphical interface but you need a terminal, use Ctrl + Alt + F2-F6 to switch to a virtual console.
Task 2: Log In Using Username and Password
Subtask 2.1: Enter Username
At the login: prompt, type your username (e.g., user1) and press Enter.
localhost login: user1  
Subtask 2.2: Enter Password
When prompted for a password, type it (no characters will be displayed for security) and press Enter.
Password:  
Expected Outcome:

Successful login displays a shell prompt:
[user1@localhost ~]$  
Troubleshooting Tip:

If login fails, verify the username and password.
If locked out, a system administrator may need to reset the password.
Task 3: Explore Virtual Terminals
Subtask 3.1: Switch Between Virtual Terminals
Linux provides multiple virtual terminals (tty1-tty6 by default).
Press Ctrl + Alt + F3 to switch to tty3.
Log in again if required.
Return to the previous terminal using Ctrl + Alt + F2.
Subtask 3.2: Check Active Terminal
Run the following command to identify the current terminal:
tty  
Expected Output:
/dev/tty2  
Subtask 3.3: List Logged-in Users
To see active sessions, run:
who  
Expected Output:
user1   tty2         2023-10-10 14:30  
user1   tty3         2023-10-10 14:35  
Troubleshooting Tip:

If switching terminals doesn’t work, ensure the system supports virtual terminals (most Linux distros do by default).
